<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>bigelovii</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>dumosa</i>, <i>Bebbia</i> <i>juncea</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>acanthocarpa</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>echinocarpa</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>farinosa</i>, <i>Ferocactus</i> <i>cylindraceus</i>, <i>Fouquieria</i> <i>splendens</i>, <i>Hyptis</i> <i>emoryi</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Pleuraphis</i> <i>rigida</i> and <i>Yucca</i> <i>schidigera</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is intermittent. Herbaceous layer is open with a cryptobiotic
crust and seasonal annuals. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Cylindropuntia bigelovii</i> > 50% relative cover in shrub layer (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, 2005).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alluvial fan deposits and gentle to moderate slopes of rocky highlands. Soils are coarse sands to loams.  </div>
</div>

        
