<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cylindropuntia bigelovii </i>is a distinctive, jointed cholla with a vertical trunk; the plant grows to 1.5 m in height. Side branches are dense, and older, lower side branches die and fall off. The yellow green flowers ripen into spineless fruits that usually contain no fertile seeds. The joints have dense spines, which are especially sharp and strongly barbed. Young spines are yellow and become black with age. During the cooler months, the terminal joints detach with the slight touch of a passing animal or even strong winds. The joints that attach to animals may be transported considerable distances. Detached joints readily grow into new plants. <br/>
<br/>
Typically, stands develop from clones of one or a few individuals (Turner et al. 1995). They occur in the southern Mojave Desert and in the Colorado Desert in a mosaic with other desert alliances, such as the <i>Larrea tridentata </i>and <i>Encelia farinosa </i>scrubs. Stands are often dense and species rich, with many succulents. Most plants are on well-drained, upper bajadas or rocky slopes with south- or southwest-facing aspects, representing a long-lived, successional species in large, almost pure stands (Vasek 1983). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
