    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-b, Cd). Plants occur in dense, nearly pure stands or swarms, and in mixed cactus stands, including those in the Carrizo Valley and Eagle Mountains (Schoenherr and Burk 2007). Stands in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998) and nearby areas of eastern San Diego Co. include the distinctive, large-statured, pink-spined hybrids (<i>Cylindropuntia</i> x <i>fosbergii</i>) and many other succulents. Holland (1986) called these stands Sonoran mixed woody and succulent scrub.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Al-m, Ao-p). Stands occupy the warmest southerly subsections. Stands in Joshua Tree National Park have <i>Encelia farinosa</i> and <i>Larrea tridentata</i> as common associates with the CNPS list 4 plant <i>Coryphantha alversonii</i> (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005). Several stands near the border of the Sonoran Desert in the Sacramento Mountains and Chemehuevi Valley contain <i>E. farinosa, L. tridentata,</i> and <i>Yucca schidigera</i> (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands are scattered throughout the moister portions of the section, associated with those of the <i>Encelia farinosa</i> or <i>Larrea tridentata- Encelia farinosa</i> alliances.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Most stands in California are in areas lacking management conflicts. However, stands are discrete and relatively few in number. Since stands are largely clonal, management should consider protection in terms of the species’ response to climatic change and non-native plant invasion. </div>
</div>

    

    

